ctly the way that you are. you're going to be t attuned to exactly the way you are. They're going to see that little hint of a smile. They're going to be able to read your mind. They're going to be able to be right there with you exactly when you need it. And no human can do that. But you never got even close to it as a kid. And so that fantasy persists. And the persistence of that fantasy makes it that it's incredibly hard for anybody to deliver it, which means you're always alone. It keeps on pushing that idea into your head that you're alone because you can't get that help that you've always wanted. And at the same time, you have a really hard time saying, "Hey, I want this. I want this. I want this." Like, "Hey, I'm like a perfect self-reliance thing is you're having sex and you're just like have a hard time saying this is exactly what makes me happy in sex because oh, if I ask for this thing that I want, if I if I ask for the help that I need, it's not going to be met. and then I'm going to have to live with the devastation that nobody is here really caring for me the way that I need it. And so you don't even ask for help because you don't want to deal with that devastation. The last one is that you have a hard time expressing when you're hurt because often times when a parent wants you to take care of them, they don't want to be faced with the misery that they're causing you. So saying that you're hurt just makes the parent feel like they're doing a bad job. Saying that you're hurt just makes your parent feel insufficient, feel even more needy or more pushing away. And therefore, they really just can't live with it. And you've been trained, okay, let's not ask for help. That's just only going to make things worse. Except for now, you're a full-g grown adult and you're not dealing with your parents. And as it turns out, a lot of people actually want to help you, but you're constantly pushing them away. A lot of people actually want to know what you want, but you're pushing them away. A lot of people want to be a great authority that you can count on, and you're pushing them away. And so, the question becomes, how do I start undoing this pattern of self-reliance? So, there's a whole bunch of resentment in your life. You resent somebody for not being there, resent somebody for not showing up, resent somebody else for not seeing you. You have this these resentments built into your life. So, write down all of those resentments. Just write them all down. And then notice how each of those things happened to you as a kid that the resentments you're holding today are the same things that your parents couldn't provide for you. It's amazing how right on the money that can be. So, that's the first one is just notice that the way you're looking at the world today isn't how the world is. you're looking at it the way that you looked at it as a little kid. Now, let's go into those five items and how you can undo each one of them. And it's kind of obvious, but some of them aren't so obvious. So, the first one is taking care of other people's emotions. A great thing to do there is just apologize whenever you're taking responsibility for somebody else's happiness. Oh, I'm so sorry that I'm disempowering you by trying to make you happy. I know that you're capable of taking care of yourself and I want to treat you that way. or hey, I'm really sorry for walking on eggshells around you and being scared of your anger. I don't want to be scared of your anger and I know that that must make you even more pissed off. Right? So, whatever it is, look for a way that you can apologize for taking on responsibility for somebody else. And if you have a hard time thinking about it, luckily you're self-reliant, which means you really understand how shitty it feels when somebody assumes that you can't take care of yourself. So, let me give you an example of that. It's like, "Oh, no, no, no, no. It's okay. I know you have a hard time writing stuff. I'll write it for you. Like, what does that make you feel inside? It's like that helplessness that you feel. That's what you're making other people feel when you're taking care of their emotional state. So, just apologizing for taking care of them and disempowering them is such a powerful tool. Another tool that you can do, if you notice that if somebody's being mean or getting mad at you, you can just express hurt. You can just say, "Ouch." So if somebody's like, "You left me all alone. You must not care about me." You can say, "Ouch." You can just respond with hurt, which allows them to know that there is pain in your system when you're being told that you're responsible for them and you're not responsible for them. Wants are easy. Every day you do 20, 30, 40 things clearly for a want. Like I want coffee. I want connection. I want someone to talk to me. I want a raise. Simple tool. Just write down here are 10 things that I want today and then say them out loud. Say each one of them out loud three or four or five times and then feel any emotion that comes up by just announcing that you want it. You can even do an EI on those emotions. We have something called emotional inquiry that will allow you to explore those feelings. But just really go into the wants that you have every day and feel into those wants. That'll start making wanting safer. And right next to that is asking for help. And this one's the easiest. Just ask for help. All you have to do is just ask for help every day. Make it a practice. Ask for help in some way. But be careful about this one because a lot of times you'll ask for help in a way that ensures that you don't get it. So often times somebody who's self-reliant feels like they can only get help from somebody who's super competent, who's going to do it exactly the right way. And of course there is no way to do it exactly the right way because that's what's in your mind and you're not expressing it. So start simple, just simple little things like, "Hey, would you help me do the dishes?" Just ask for help in these little ways and start noticing, "Oh, is there any way I'm sabotaging my ask for help? I'm asking for help in doing dishes, but I haven't asked for the dishes to be rinsed before they go into the washing machine. So, I know I'm going to be disappointed because I know my daughter never washes the plate before it goes into the washing machine." So just look for simple ways that you are asking for help in a way to make sure you don't get what you want. And then the last one is the authority issue. So one of the things about authority issues is that most people have a problem with authority have a hard time being in authority. They have a hard time owning the thing that they know. Now of course none of us are perfect. Everybody makes mistakes. But see what it's like every day to take a deep breath and own something that you know and own it with certainty. And if somebody disagrees that's fine, you could be wrong. But just take that moment to own the thing you know with certainty. And so what that means is being in your system being upright. You're not trying to convince them because you're certain. Why would you have to convince them? You're not hesitating. You're not hedging well kind of maybe I know this. You're just upright in yourself. say, "Oh, I know this," or, "Here's the thing that I that I think." And then do that with a big open heart. Because what's really important about owning your own authority and doing it with an open heart is it starts to show you that authority can have an open heart. That an authority doesn't have to be pushy and doesn't have to be needy. An authority can actually just be upright in themselves. And so, that's a really great practice. There are a ton of other practices you can do, but if you just do those, it'll be a great start on your self-reliance issues. But the most important thing in working with self-reliance is just the simple recognition that you are not alone, right? 